vage division occurs approximately \u003Cstrong\u003E30 hours\u003C/strong\u003E after fertilisation. This results in two identical blastomeres. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubsequent divisions occur every 12-15 hours, with the \u003Cstrong\u003E48-hour\u003C/strong\u003E embryo typically having four cells. By \u003Cstrong\u003E72 hours\u003C/strong\u003E, the embryo usually has eight cells. At \u003Cstrong\u003E96 hours\u003C/strong\u003E, the embryo has 16-32 cells and is beginning to form a morula. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese early cleavage divisions are mitotic divisions that increase cell number without increasing overall size, as the embryo remains confined within the zona pellucida. Each blastomere becomes progressively smaller with each division.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first cleavage division in human embryos occurs approximately 30 hours after fertilisation."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48351"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48351"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T11:30:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T11:31:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8548"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62900"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n